<br>
In my mind, the only advantage that an Orion offers is that it can be adopted to fusion power.  As such, it represents the only way we now have for tapping fusion as a propulsion system.<br>
<br>
If you are just using fission, however, there are plenty of more elegant solotions than Orion.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2072<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/24/03 3:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=304.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Re: A nuclear fission type orion for interplanetary fli</span><hr size=1> I think that both have their place, just as some trips on Earth  require a large truck while other trips only require a motorcycle to get the job done.  I hope that transportation is as diverse in space in the not too distant future...<br>
<br>
That being said, I believe that Carl Sagan said in his book 'Cosmos', that an Orion may be able to achieve 10% the speed of light.  Too slow for voyages across the stellar void, but really smokes the NSWR in terms of speed!<br>
