There is that, but it probably only applies to such monstrosities as the mythical &quot;super&quot; ship, of tens of millions of tons. Not to put it down -it is still theoretically 1960s tech, but it may be overkill!!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; If you are just using fission, however, there are plenty of more elegant solutions than Orion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
My point about archaic tech is important. Are virtually all major parts of these 'elegant solutions' as well known? Laboratory curiosities or industrial applications? (not that atomic explosives are industrial tools, but they are like weeds nowadays -popping up all over the place).<br>
Fission is also cheaper. Even if a ship could use 500Kt bombs in place of 15 or .5kt bombs, it may still be cheaper to use more little ones.<br>
<br>
Zubrin speaks of the NSWR, Chang-Diaz talks about VASIMR, others have their favorites, but<br>
