<br>
True, NSWR are unproven and still in the rough concept phase and VASIMR is still just a prototype.  However, Orion never got past the prototype phase either and all the advanced design work that was done was done in a relatively short time.  It would not take long for NSWR to be developed to the same level of maturity as Orion.  <br>
<br>
In addition, there are a whole bevy of NEP schemes that can be implimented today and have been flight tested, at least piecewise, in space.  The challenge of building a nuclear reactor in space is a well understood one.  Indeed, the SNAP 10 was launched and operated successfully in space in the 1960, something of which the Orion can not boast.  Once we have generator capacity, linking it to one of the many working and time tested eletrical propulsion technologies is a simple matter.  <br>
<br>
This sort of NEP, while not as spectacular or potentialy powerful as the Orion, has the double advantage of being able to launch now, and being able to power much smaller craft, such as small interplanetary probes.<br>
<br>
This interim solution should be more than enough to send us on our way into the solar system while the more powerful technologies, such as Orion and NSWR, are evaluated and developed.<br>
<br>
As I have stated before, my personal preference lies with NSWR.  I am not a nuclear engineer, so I am unable to evaluate each technology with the thoroughness it deserves.  Indeed, I cannot make the conclusion on my own as to whether or not each technology will even work, for that I must simply trust the designers.  Yet there are a few things that strike me about each technology, and these are what I will now enumerate.<br>
<br>
1) Orion requires an enourmously massive pusher plate to capture the force of the propulsive blast.  In addition  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/1/03 12:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=304.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Continued from above</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(edited for spelling - Megalo)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
Orion also requires heavy shock absorbers to spread the felt acceleration out over a longer time, so as not to smash the occupants.  In general, the Orion has to be built like an armored battleship.  This makes me very skeptical about claims of 3/1 or 5/1 mass ratios that I often hear.  <br>
<br>
To be fair, these mass penalties must be weighed against the fact that the NSWR has to store it's salt water propellent in thin, neutron absorbing pipes, which probably weigh a lot. <br>
<br>
2)Orion is propelled by nuclear explosions, which result in EMP damage and fallout when operated in the vicinity or Earth.  The EMP could be enough to fry any satellites in nearby orbits as well as earth-based electronics below.<br>
<br>
In contrast, the NSWR, while still generating radioactive exhaust, emits it in a concentrated directional stream that can be pointed away from Earth.  I am unclear as to whether or not a NSWR would generate any sort of EM interference, I have never heard that issue addressed directly.<br>
<br>
3)Nuclear explosions are illegal in space.  Continuous nuclear detonations are not.<br>
<br>
While this is really just a political issue, it is an international political issue.  We should, at least, make an effort to pay lip service to international cooperation.  Most nations may not be able to find their own ass if you handed it to them on a silver platter, but that does not mean we should go out of our way to piss them off.  <br>
<br>
The US is already walking on thin ice at this point due to the ABM treaty, the Kyoto protocol, and the Land Mine Treaty.  We have already performed our share of unilateral treaty withdrawels, to try for more right now would be pushing our luck. <br>
<br>
In general, NSWR is easier to swing from a political standpoint.<br>
<br>
These are but a few points that lead me to place my support where I do.<br>
<br>
Ultimately, the deciding factor as to whether each technology enters active service will be economic.  I do not have the technical knowledge to make a judgement as to which technology will be more affordable, but I see no reson why it could not be NSWR.<br>
<br>
While bombs currently exist, they would have to be adapted to Orion before they could be used as pus.  This would probably be no easier than extracting their fissionables and mixing them with water.  <br>
<br>
I think we should still look at all technologies fairly.  There may be application that one could do better than the other.  But I do not agree with  the common oppinion on this board that Orion is the logical next step. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A> at: 3/1/03 11:57:35 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 379<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/2/03 6:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=304.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   feasibility &amp; acceptability</span><hr size=1> (was Re: Continued from above)<br>
<br>
The so-called &quot;mass penalties&quot; due to the heavy pusher plate, shock absorber system, and the strong structure itself are advantages of Orion.<br>
As I wrote elsewhere recently, the heavy plate &amp; shocks aren't penalties, but enablers. They let us take advantage of the raw power &amp; simplicity of the atomic bomb to get around space faster &amp; safer than any other proposal as easily built.<br>
 Remember that bombs are the first way we exploited atomic energy, and are the simplest and also the most <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>emphatic</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> way to get the massive amounts of energy in nuclear fuels. Any other method of using atomic energy has difficulties in containing the energy, limiting the available power because of materials limitations. External nuclear pulse rockets don't try to contain anything, we let it go BANG! with the maximum possible energy output.<br>
 Simple mechanical shock absorbers allow us to do this, and so we have abundant power left over for massive brutal structures in the ships, and aalso extreme performance from those ships.<br>
 I actually like the (requirement for &amp;/or ability to utilize) heavy battleship-like structure. Add in plenty of redundancies in systems and pathways &amp; conduits, extra heavy-duty fittings, lots of spares stores, tools &amp; machine shops. Far preferable to skimpy fragile structures in any other ship design which doesn't have thousands of tons lifting/pushing capacity.<br>
<br>
If you doubt the mass ratio claims, or the performance, or the physics, then do the numbers and show without a doubt that General Atomics, the USAF, NASA, DARPA and the many qualified engineers &amp; scientists who worked up the designs we get these performance figures from, are wrong. We go from information published in educated-layman terms, by authors &amp; reviewers who have followed the engineering papers from the designers. We aren't just throwing around big numbers on our own.<br>
<br>
Show a source for data proving that EMP is a threat from orbital pulses of less than 10-20Kt (a 10 or 20 meter ship, built up from loads lifted by HLVs). Small pulses which not only aren't designed to maximize EMP, but may even be made to minimize or eliminate it.<br>
I'll save you the work: Everything we've seen says that EMP is a problem in high atmosphere bursts of multiple megatons plus, or much smaller blasts which have been specially made to maximize EMP.<br>
<br>
As for the political issues, multinational cooperation is called for -Orion is a perfect way to forge multinational cooperation in interplanetary spaceflight.<br>
 I don't care what the present situation is, or what the US current status in international treaties is (crappy). This could be a huge multinational project, generating interest from all over the planet, with people from all over working on it. Everything from getting the former warheads Pu, to explosives in space, to space resources use calls for multinational cooperation.<br>
A couple of articles about this<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.cdi.org/russia/johnson/5550-12.cfm">Part 1</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.skali.com/index.php?ch=3&amp;pg=152&amp;ac=342&amp;ct=">Part 2</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
OTOH, I'd really like to see China or Greenpeace or anybody else protest a unilateral use of Orion in space. What, they'll tell the UN or the press that they don't like the fact that we're doing a mission which incidentally burns up a few hundred warheads worth of weapons-grade Pu? They'd rather we keep it here on the ground, maybe in bombs (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>weapons</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, that is), maybe just collecting dust somewhere?<br>
<br>
As for the &quot;political fallout&quot; from protestors, I doubt it'd be that much harder to swing an Orion than any other big nuclear project in space. Once you get the clout to override the hysteria about polluting the solar wind, NPR is as easy to get flying as Nuke thermal or NSWR -and easier technically and better performance -the performance is what really wins it from a perspective of mission architecture planning.<br>
